{
  "texts": [
    "The message of (§4) is that these are defeated by the Strict Bodily Constraint, derived from the Davidsonian standard story of action.",
    "Davidson's account makes sense of the appeal of HEC (multiple action descriptions are available, including descriptions of the action as cognitive) but does so in instrumental terms (multiple causally linked actions and worldly events are what account for the correctness of any such description).",
    "At the core of this argument is the A-D Principle.",
    "This provides the theoretical basis for Davidson's slogan that agents only ever move their bodies.",
    "If only bodily movements are actions, then only these movements (and not their cognitively relevant consequences) can be constitutive of what an agent does."
  ]
}